==English==

===Etymology===
Origin uncertain; reportedly a jocular coinage by Bell Labs supervisor Don Macpherson in the early 1960s, from ''[[octo-]]'' (with reference to the eight points) + ''-thorpe'' (after 1912 Olympic medalist Jim Thorpe, in whom Macpherson had some interest).  The story is disputed by some etymologists.  At least two other accounts of its creation by AT&T engineers have appeared in 2006; Doug Kerr[http://doug.kerr.home.att.net/pumpkin/index.htm#Octatherp] attributes "octatherp" to engineers John C. Schaak and Herbert T. Uthlaut; Lauren Asplund attributes "octotherp" to Howard Eby and himself (in reverted wikipedia and wiktionary edits).  ''The Merriam-Webster New Book of Word Histories,'' 1991, supports "octotherp" as the original spelling, and telephone engineers as the source.

